Project overview

The goal of the NASTE project was to test how different sources of enrichment influence corals with and without thermal stress. We used four differnt enrichment sources, seabird guano, wastewater effluent, inorganic nutrients, and a control seawater, in this 83 day long experiment. Two species of coral, Montipora capitata and Porites compressa, were used, and half of the corals were also run through a simulated bleaching event (MMM +3 C) from days 40-54 (Mcap) and 40-55 (Pcom). The photochemical efficiency (FvFm) of each coral fragment was measured weekly to determine how the different enrichment and heat treatments were affecting photosynthesis.

GAMS

Utilizing a gam model structure to capture the non-linear response of FvFm to the different treatments.

PORITES

  # Model 1 -different slope and different intercept
  # Model 2 - same slope and different intercept
  # Model 3 - global smoother assuming no treatment differences by day

Plot_differences

Compare each treatment to their heated counterpart

# Define a list of your comparisons
comparisons <- list(
  list(name = "ch_ca", difference = c("control.Heated", "control.Ambient"), title = "Control Heated vs. Control Ambient"),
  list(name = "eh_ea", difference = c("effluent.Heated", "effluent.Ambient"), title = "Effluent Heated vs. Effluent Ambient"),
  list(name = "gh_ga", difference = c("guano.Heated", "guano.Ambient"), title = "Guano Heated vs. Guano Ambient"),
  list(name = "ih_ia", difference = c("inorganic.Heated", "inorganic.Ambient"), title = "Inorganic Heated vs. Inorganic Ambient")
)

# Loop through each comparison to generate plots
plots <- list()  # Initialize an empty list to store plots

for (comp in comparisons) {
  plot <- plot_difference(
    pc_pam_1,
    series = day,
    difference = list(trt_temp = comp$difference)
  ) + ggtitle(comp$title)

# max heated value is 0.553 and min is 0.219, range is 0.334

Max heated FvFm value is 0.553 and min is 0.219, range is 0.334. Inorganic was approx. 9% lower than control, 12% lower than effluent, and 18% lower than guano during max heat (and through recovery for guano).Guano was 15% higher than control and 11.2% higher than effluent corals during max heat and early recovery. Control and effluent were similar.

Overall interpretation of Porites - heat significantly decreased FvFm values in all treatments, guano had the smallest difference (32.8%) and inorganic had the greatest difference (44.8%). With the addition of nutrient treatments to ambient corals, both effluent and guano supported higher FvFm values compared to control and inorganic treatments, but only between days 45-65 (ish). During the interaction of heat x treatment, guano corals performed significantly better than the other 3 treatments, while inorganic corals had significantly lower FvFm values than the other 3 treatments.

Significance: Guano supported photochemical efficiency in corals with and without heat. Effluent supported photochemical efficiency without heat, but when heat was introduced it performed no different than the control corals. The addition of just nutrients (inorganic) without the rest of the ‘stuff’ in each source had the greatest negative impact on the corals.

## Plot_differences

Compare each treatment to their heated counterpart

# Define a list of your comparisons
comparisons <- list(
  list(name = "ch_ca", difference = c("control.Heated", "control.Ambient"), title = "Control Heated vs. Control Ambient"),
  list(name = "eh_ea", difference = c("effluent.Heated", "effluent.Ambient"), title = "Effluent Heated vs. Effluent Ambient"),
  list(name = "gh_ga", difference = c("guano.Heated", "guano.Ambient"), title = "Guano Heated vs. Guano Ambient"),
  list(name = "ih_ia", difference = c("inorganic.Heated", "inorganic.Ambient"), title = "Inorganic Heated vs. Inorganic Ambient")
)

# Loop through each comparison to generate plots
plots <- list()  # Initialize an empty list to store plots

for (comp in comparisons) {
  plot <- plot_difference(
    mc_pam_4,
    series = day,
    difference = list(trt_temp = comp$difference)
  ) + ggtitle(comp$title)
    plots[[comp$name]] <- plot
}

# Display plots
grid.arrange(
  plots$ch_ca,
  plots$eh_ea,
  plots$gh_ga,
  plots$ih_ia,
  ncol = 2  
)

#### Heat was introduced on day 40, inorganic and effluent started diverging on day 30, while control was at day 40 and guano not until a few days into heating. Max FvFm value in dataset was 0.578 and min was 0.141, total range of 0.437. The introduction of heat approximately decreased FvFm values by 20.5% in control corals, 17.2% in effluent corals, 22.9% in guano corals, and 22.9% in inorganic corals. Percentages found by looking at each max difference/0.437. Eg for control 0.09/0.437=0.205

# Define a list of the new comparisons

  list(name = "ih_ch", difference = c("inorganic.Heated", "control.Heated"), title = "Inorganic Heated vs. Control Heated"),
  list(name = "eh_gh", difference = c("effluent.Heated", "guano.Heated"), title = "Effluent Heated vs. Guano Heated"),
  list(name = "ih_eh", difference = c("inorganic.Heated", "effluent.Heated"), title = "Inorganic Heated vs. Effluent Heated"),
  list(name = "ih_gh", difference = c("inorganic.Heated", "guano.Heated"), title = "Inorganic Heated vs. Guano Heated")
)

# Initialize an empty list to store the new plots
heat_plots <- list()

# Loop through each new comparison to generate plots
for (comp in heat_comparisons) {
  plot <- plot_difference(

    difference = list(trt_temp = comp$difference)
  ) + ggtitle(comp$title)
    heat_plots[[comp$name]] <- plot

  heat_plots$eh_gh,
  heat_plots$ih_eh,
  heat_plots$ih_gh,
  ncol = 2  
)

#### There are differenecs between treatments. The max ambient FvFm value is 0.574 and min is 0.141, the range of values is 0.433. Control is approx. 8.7% lower than effluent days 10-19 and 52-62, no different than guano or inorganic. Inorganic is 6.8% lower than effluent (days 50-67) and 16.2% lower than guano (days 25-48). Effluent is 5.8% higher than guano days 10-12, but 11.5% lower than guano days 25-48 and 72-76.

Overall interpreation of Montipora: Heat decreased FvFm in all treatments from about 17.2% in effluent corals to 22.9% in guano and inorganic corals. In ambient corals, guano supported slightly (5-9%) higher FvFm values than inorganic or control corals, respectively. The interaction of heat x treatment caused control corals to be significantly lower (8.7%) than effluent corals, but no different from guano or inorganic corals. Effluent and guano were significantly higher than inorganic corals (6.8% and 16.2%, respectively). Guano corals were 11.5% higher than effluent corals BEFORE heating, but no different during/after heating.
